I almost got kicked out of college because I couldn’t afford it. 

I was the only person in my household to graduate from university, so navigating the complexities of FAFSA, Pell Grants and scholarships at 17 with little help was overwhelming. During my first semester at UGA I had misfiled some paperwork related to my financial aid and I was on a tight deadline to correct it before I would be removed from all of my classes and locked out of university housing. 

Thankfully, I figured it out, and I graduated four years later with an honors GPA, Presidential Distinction, and a prestigious job at a consulting firm in NYC. 

I figured it out. And if you’re in college right now or even a few years into your career, I guess I want you to know that whatever hardships or challenges you’re going through right now, you’ll figure those out as well. You just have to keep moving forward.

Getting married to you last year was one of the biggest mistakes of my life. Because it forced me to confront my fear that growing closer to someone would somehow hold me back, even though being married to you has only made me stronger.

I wasn’t always surrounded with the best model for a supportive relationship, as you know, and before we met I used this as an excuse to why I could never see myself in a marriage. 

But you’ve never stopped challenging me, and I am continuously in awe at how much grace, joy and wonder you bring to our life. 

When I asked you to marry me, it wasn’t because I thought I was the perfect man or partner. I asked you because you were the first person in my life who believed that I could be.

Happy anniversary, Kaylee

I don’t deserve my job. 

I’ve never believed that life was fair. And I don’t think you should, either.

Whether in dating, investing, or your career you won’t get what you deserve, you’ll get what you’re worth.

And in my case, earlier this year when I was looking for more in my career, I was able to rely on my professional network to secure an amazing role, with a 30% pay increase, in an industry I had no experience in.

There were certainly other people in consideration for this role with more experience, and more industry knowledge, than me. But because of who I knew, I got the job. Even though I never even applied!

The best jobs aren’t posted on LinkedIn.

The best investment opportunities aren’t on Robinhood.

The best partners (most likely) aren’t on dating apps.

Once you become skilled at creating private, interpersonal networks, you will never have to wonder where your next opportunity will come from. Hell, they may come looking for you!

If you’re curious about how to get started, I spent two months pouring everything I know about networking into a complete guide. And this weekend, I’m offering it at a great discount before I take it away forever.

This week is your last chance to get my course on Networking. After that, I’m taking it down and I don’t know when I’ll be offering it again.

Seriously.

Use code ‘BF2023’ for a 50% off discount!

Enjoy your holiday season, and I can’t wait to show you what I’ve got in store for 2024.

If you’re like most people, the Monday after a long holiday weekend hits harder than most. 

If you opened your laptop this morning and immediately said: “WTF”, here are a few tips to help ease your way back into my work. 

1. The best days start the night before. If you can make a to-do list of any urgent items you need to tackle first thing, it’ll make you more proactive and less reactive

2. Use momentum to your advantage. Categorize your inbox, respond to some slack messages, do something small to build up momentum to carry you through your day

3. Remember that everyone else, in the US at least, had some time off last week too. So don’t be too hard on yourself!

If you found this helpful - share it! And follow @careercolin for more tips like these.

1. Start with yourself. The nicest clothes can’t help a non optimal frame. Eat well, try to stick to a workout routine and explore starting a skincare routine as well. This won’t just help you look better, but you’ll be setting yourself up to be more alert and productive at work as well. Did you know the most common trait of F500 CEOs is that they workout regularly?

2. Get inspired. I still to this day save outfits on Pinterest, Instagram, etc and come back to them when it’s time to get some new clothes. Try to figure out the intersection of what you like, what’s common in your field, and what’s popular in the current moment. 

3. Think in pieces, buy in seasons. I only buy new clothes a few times per year, typically as it gets colder or warmer. But when I buy, I’m looking for items that can be a bridge between what I wear now and where I’m trying to go. Don’t buy one really sick outfit that doesn’t go with anything else in your closet! Aim for versatility, and remember that neutral colors will match with the most other pieces in your wardrobe! #style #work #office #corporate #fashion

Starting 2024 off with intense reflection on what I’ve accomplished, and where I want to head in the future. 

What began as me posting a “day in the life” TikTok of me working in consulting almost three years ago has blossomed into a global community of over 230,000 professionals, mentors, students, CEOs, and more, and provided me with more reach, income and influence than I ever thought was possible. 

But my goal has never been to be an influencer. At the end of the day my biggest objective when it comes to this page is to use my platform, access, and privilege to open up as many opportunities as I can for anyone trying to get to the next level in their own professional journey, especially if they are the first in their family to do so. 

Whether you’ve been following me for years, months, or just saw one viral video and decided to check me out, thank you so much for the views, the comments, and the DMs just saying “this helped me”. You have no idea how much life that gives me to keep sharing and keep creating. 

I’ve got so much more left to give.

As a first generation professional, getting my first job in consulting required me to learn the world of corporate America from the ground up.

If you’re interested in learning more - comment ‘consulting’ below!
